Barplots in ggplot2

library(ggplot2)
library(ggthemes)
data("diamonds")

As discussed in scatterplots with ggplot2, most plots begin in ggplot function. The first argument is the data set, the second argument is the mapping. The mapping is usually used in conjucntion with aes (short for aesthetics) function. This gives the main arguments of the plot. Below we create a basic barplot.

ggplot(diamonds, aes(cut))+
  geom_bar()

Lets adjust the barwidth

ggplot(diamonds, aes(cut))+
  geom_bar(width = 0.5)

To add some more color, lets color the outside of the bars blue and the inisde (fill) green. To outside of parenthesis tell R to print the object after it is defined.

(bar1 <- ggplot(diamonds, aes(cut))+
    geom_bar(width = 0.5, colour = 'blue', fill = 'green'))

Relabel the axes and flip the plot

bar1+
  labs(x = 'Cut', y = 'Count')+
  coord_flip()

Lets say you wanted to color each cut differently, rather than all green or all black.

ggplot(diamonds, aes(cut, fill = cut))+
  geom_bar(width = 0.5)

In the examples so far, ggplot has produced the count for each different type of cut in the diamonds data set. However, what if you had the counts already and wanted to make a bar plot. For example, lets say that on a math exam there were 10 As, 7 Bs, 6 Cs, 5 Ds and 2 Fs, and you wanted to make a barplot of this. You can use the stat = identity argument in your barplot. This is shown in the code below.

dat <- data.frame(grade = c('A', 'B', 'C', 'D', 'F'), count = c(10, 13, 6, 5, 2), 
                  description =c('Excellet', 'Good', 'Satisfactory', 'Poor', 'Unsatisfactory'))
ggplot(dat, aes(x = grade, y = count))+
  geom_bar(stat = 'identity', width = 0.5)

If your x axis labels are crowded, you can adjust the angle of the text using the element_text function in conjunction with the theme function. Use the arguments hjust = 1 and vjust =1 for horizontal and vertical alignment respectively of the text. For example, in the code below, we use the description of the grade instead of the letter grade, we call theme_calc(), then we adjust the text to appear at 45 degree angle.

ggplot(dat, aes(x = description, y = count))+
  geom_bar(stat = 'identity', width = 0.5)+
  theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 45, hjust = 1, vjust = 1))+
  labs(x = "Grade Category", y = "Count")+
  theme_calc()

Sometimes we may want to order our barplot differently. The two above barplots are ordered from left to right in alphabetical order. However, what if we had wanted to order the grades based on the category with the most to least students. We can use the function to specify the order. The first argument is the variable that is being reordered, in this example description, the second vector specifies the order in which you want to order that vector from lowest to highest.

ggplot(dat, aes(x = reorder(description, count), y = count))+
  geom_bar(stat = 'identity', width = 0.5)+
  theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 45, hjust = 1, vjust = 1))+
  labs(x = "Grade Category", y = "Count")+
  theme_calc()

This is in ascending order. If we wnated to order in descending order we could use a minus sign on count in the function.

ggplot(dat, aes(x = reorder(description, -count), y = count))+
  geom_bar(stat = 'identity', width = 0.5)+
  theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 45, hjust = 1, vjust = 1))+
  labs(x = "Grade Category", y = "Count")+
  theme_calc()

We could specify another numeric vector. For example, since is listed from Excellent to Unsatisfactory, we could list use the vector , thereby plotting Excellent first, Good second and so forth.

ggplot(dat, aes(x = reorder(description, 1:5) , y = count))+
  geom_bar(stat = 'identity', width = 0.5)+
  theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 45, hjust = 1, vjust = 1))+
  labs(x = "Grade Category", y = "Count")+
  theme_calc()

Returning to our diamonds data set, you could fill by a different categorical variable. For example lets create a barplot of cut but fill up the bars by the different levels of clarity. This may give us an idea of whether the cut varies by the clarity much.

ggplot(diamonds, aes(cut, fill = clarity))+
  geom_bar(width = 0.5)

We can create different barplots for each color by using the function facet_wrap

ggplot(diamonds, aes(cut, fill = clarity))+
  geom_bar(width = 0.5)+
  facet_wrap(~ color)

This would probably look better if we first tried to minimize the number of windows.There are 5 cuts, 8 levels of clarity and 7 colors lets try two do a facet wrap by cut instead wrap by cut, make barplots of the clarity levels with the fill by color.

(bar2 <- ggplot(diamonds, aes(clarity, fill = color))+
    geom_bar(width = 0.5)+
    facet_wrap(~ cut))

Lets add axes label, flip the coordinates

bar2 +
  labs(x = 'Cut', y = 'Count')+
  coord_flip()

You can use the facet grid function to stack all five cuts next to each other.

bar2 +
  labs(x = 'Cut', y = 'Count')+
  coord_flip()+
  facet_grid(.~cut)+
  theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 90, hjust = 1, vjust = 1))
